Taking the dot product of both sides with $\mathbf{n},$ we get
\[\mathbf{n} \cdot \mathbf{r} = \mathbf{n} \cdot \mathbf{v} + k \mathbf{n} \cdot \mathbf{n}.\]Since $\mathbf{n}$ is orthogonal to plane $P,$ $\mathbf{n} \cdot \mathbf{r} = -\mathbf{n} \cdot \mathbf{v},$ so
\[-\mathbf{n} \cdot \mathbf{v} = \mathbf{n} \cdot \mathbf{v} - k |\mathbf{n}|^2.\]Then $k = \frac{2 \mathbf{n} \cdot \mathbf{v}}{|\mathbf{n}|^2},$ so
\[\mathbf{r} = \mathbf{v} - \frac{2 \mathbf{n} \cdot \mathbf{v}}{|\mathbf{n}|^2} \mathbf{n}.\]Hence,
\[\mathbf{R} = \mathbf{I} - \frac{2 \mathbf{n} \cdot \mathbf{v}}{|\mathbf{n}|^2} \mathbf{n} \mathbf{n}^T.\]If $\mathbf{v} = \begin{pmatrix} x \\ y \\ z \end{pmatrix},$ then $\mathbf{n} \cdot \mathbf{v} = x + y - z.$  Also, $|\mathbf{n}|^2 = 1^2 + 1^2 + (-1)^2 = 3,$ so
\[\mathbf{R} = \begin{pmatrix} 1 & 0 & 0 \\ 0 & 1 & 0 \\ 0 & 0 & 1 \end{pmatrix} - \frac{2}{3} \begin{pmatrix} 1 \\ 1 \\ -1 \end{pmatrix} \begin{pmatrix} 1 & 1 & -1 \end{pmatrix} = \boxed{\begin{pmatrix} -\frac{1}{3} & \frac{2}{3} & \frac{2}{3} \\ \frac{2}{3} & -\frac{1}{3} & \frac{2}{3} \\ \frac{2}{3} & \frac{2}{3} & \frac{1}{3} \end{pmatrix}}.\]

